## 📜 Back to History

### Challenge: **Creeper**

The **Creeper virus**, created in 1971, is widely regarded as the world’s first self-replicating computer program.

| Key Fact | Details |
| --- | --- |
| **Creator** | Bob Thomas (1971) |
| **Organization** | Raytheon BBN Technologies |
| **System Targeted** | DEC PDP-10 mainframes running TENEX |
| **Network Used** | ARPANET (precursor to the Internet) |
| **Message** | *"I’m the creeper, catch me if you can!"* |

#### How it Worked

Creeper was an experimental test of autonomous code movement. It copied itself over ARPANET, printed a file, halted, and moved to another system, erasing its prior copy.

#### The Reaper Connection

To counter Creeper, **Ray Tomlinson** wrote **Reaper**, a self-propagating utility that deleted Creeper. Reaper is recognized as the **first antivirus program**, marking the beginning of the cybersecurity threat-defense cycle.

